\markboth{Abstract}{}

\begin{abstract}
We study a nonlinear extension of the multi-asset Black-Scholes equation, which incorporates a state dependant valuation adjustments, such as funding and credit cost. Using a sequance of transformations we reduce the pricing problem to a semilinear heat equation.

\[
\partial_\tau u - \Delta u + f(u) = 0, \qquad (\tau,z)\in \mathbb{R}_+ \times \mathbb{R}^d.
\]
We focus our analysis on two piecewise-linear nonlinearities, which are meant to encode discounting on positive and negative mark-to-market values. Under a global Lipshitz condition, we establish global well-posedness and instantaneous $H^1$ regularization. In the dissipative case, we further obtain energy identities, $L^2$ contraction, and algebraic decay. In contrast, the non-dissipative model admits only Gronwall-type growth bounds together with exponentially weighted Gagliardo--Nirenberg estimates, highlighting the competition between funding effects and risk-free discounting. Finally, these analytical results are transported back to the original Black-Scholes variables.

\end{abstract}
