\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}
Derivative contracts are fundamental to the functioning of the modern financial market and the economy as a whole. They are used in almost every sector of the economy, along the entire supply chain, to hedge risk associated with interest rate/exchange rate fluctuations and input cost prices, such as petrol and gas, and to insure assets. More generally, a derivative is a contract between parties for the exchange of fixing some sort of financial terms ahead of time. This raises the question of how one is supposed to price these contracts. How much does the risk for the party exposed—like the issuer of a call option, for example-cost, and what is a fair compensation for that risk?

The foundational theory of derivatives pricing comes from \cite{BlackScholes1973} and \cite{Merton1973}. They established that no-arbitrage pricing leads to a parabolic partial differential equation. At the core of their model is the idea that assets follow a geometric Brownian motion. Their approach argues that under the no-arbitrage condition, the price of a financial derivative should be the price of replicating a locally riskless portfolio, where by hedging you isolate the volatile ups and downs. And since it is riskless, you should be earning the market-wide risk-free rate. This approach yields an elegant linear pricing equation, which can also be easily extended to a multi-asset setting. Even though the underlying mathematics becomes more tricky since we are dealing with correlated Brownian motion, the core argument of constructing a replicating portfolio is the same.

The classical model is analytically powerful precisely because it removes many market frictions: volatility is constant, liquidity is perfect, transaction costs are absent, and borrowing and lending occur at a single risk-free rate. For this paper, the last simplification is the most relevant. In practice, deposits and credit do not generate symmetric funding costs. This simple economic asymmetry has a strong effect on the pricing formula, since it breaks the linearity of the classical Black-Scholes equation.

This asymmetry in discounting costs has motivated the \emph{total value} approach to derivatives pricing. One of the early contributions to nonlinear derivatives pricing is \cite{BurgardKjaer2011}, who showed that when a bank cannot borrow and deposit at the risk-free rate, linearity breaks down because the valuation adjustment depends recursively on the unknown price. They therefore extend the linear Black--Scholes equation by introducing a nonlinear funding term. Since many contracts can be viewed as insurance written against a broader portfolio of assets, we follow a similar modeling philosophy and generalize the framework to $d>1$ underlying assets.

We are thus led to the nonlinear multi-asset pricing equation
\begin{equation}
V_t
+ \frac{1}{2}\sum_{i,j=1}^d Q_{ij}S_iS_j V_{S_iS_j}
+ r\sum_{i=1}^d S_i V_{S_i}
- rV
- g(V) = 0,
\label{eq:intro_nonlin_bs}
\end{equation}
with terminal condition $V(T,S)=\Phi(S)$. Here $Q$ is a symmetric
positive definite covariance matrix, and the nonlinear term $g(V)$
represents a state-dependent valuation adjustment capturing the
asymmetry between borrowing and lending rates.

A prototypical specification is
\[
g(v) = a\,v^+ - b\,v^-, \qquad a,b \ge 0,
\]
which applies different effective discounting rates to positive and
negative exposures. For example, a positive exposure (an asset) may be
funded at a lower rate $a$, while a negative exposure (a liability) incurs
a higher funding cost $b$, reflecting real market conditions.

We also consider an alternative model
\[
g(v) = a\,v^+ + b\,v^-, \qquad a,b \ge 0.
\]

Notice that in this model the positive branch has the same behavior as
the previous one, but on the negative exposure branch it actually
amplifies the rate. Mathematically speaking, this creates a
non-dissipative behavior. Economically speaking, this can be interpreted
as a benefit associated with holding liabilities. For example, one not
only receives funding, which can be invested, but also effectively
discounts the contract against its own default risk. In this sense, we
adjust the price of the contract to reflect that negative exposures might
generate effective benefits.

The aim of this paper is to establish a rigorous analytical framework for these two nonlinear valuation problems. Due to the intrinsic difference in their respective behaviors, we separate the analysis of the
dissipative and non-dissipative models. For both models jointly we
establish well-posedness in weighted $L^2$ spaces and derive smoothing
results under Lipschitz and piecewise-linear assumptions. For the
dissipative core model $f_-(u)=a u^+ - b u^-$ we additionally establish
comparison, contraction, and decay properties. The non-dissipative
extension $f_+(u)=a u^+ + b u^-$ is treated separately using bounds
adapted to the lack of monotonicity.

\begin{remark}[Sign convention under time reversal]
\label{rem:sign_convention}
Throughout this thesis, we pass from the financial pricing PDE, which is
posed backward in time, to a forward parabolic heat-type equation. To do
this we use a change of variables, time reversal, and discounting. Under
this transformation the nonlinear term $g(V)$ changes sign and becomes a
reaction term of the form $+f(u)$ in the forward equation.
\end{remark}

\medskip
\noindent\textbf{Main results.}
The principal results of this paper are as follows.
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*)]

\item \emph{Global $L^2$ well-posedness}. Under the global Lipschitz condition, the equation has a unique global mild solution $\tilde u\in C([0,\infty);L^2(\mathbb{R}^d))$ with continuous dependence on the initial datum; see Theorem~\ref{thm:L2_global_wp}. For the pricing PDE, this means that the contract price depends continuously on the payoff.

\item \emph{Parabolic smoothing and $H^1$ well-posedness}
(Section~\ref{subsec:H1_instantaneous_regularization},
Theorem~\ref{thm:H1_piecewise_wp}).
For $L^2$ initial data, the solution exhibits instantaneous parabolic
smoothing for all $\tau>0$, and for $H^1$ initial data it remains
globally in $C([0,\infty);H^1(\mathbb{R}^d))$. This means that the
pricing function becomes smooth immediately and remains well-behaved.

\item \emph{Dissipative model: contraction and decay}
(Section~\ref{sec:dissipative_model}).
For $f_-(u)=au^+-bu^-$, the sign condition $f_-(s)s\ge 0$ yields an
$L^2$ energy identity and contraction, together with algebraic decay
\[
  \|\tilde u(\tau)\|_{L^2}^2
  \lesssim \|\tilde u_0\|_{L^1}^2\,\tau^{-d/2}, \qquad \tau\to\infty,
\]
for $\tilde u_0\in L^1(\mathbb{R}^d)\cap L^2(\mathbb{R}^d)$.
After back-translation,
\[
\|V(t)\|_{L^2_\omega}\lesssim
e^{-r(T-t)}\|\Phi\|_{L^1_\omega}(T-t)^{-d/4}.
\]

\item \emph{Non-dissipative plus-model bounds}
(Section~\ref{sec:plus_model}).
For $f_+(u)=au^++bu^-$, dissipativity is lost and no contraction holds.
Instead, we obtain the Gr\"onwall bound
\[
\|\tilde u(\tau)\|_{L^2}^2
\le e^{2b\tau}\|\tilde u_0\|_{L^2}^2,
\]
together with an exponentially weighted Gagliardo--Nirenberg estimate.
After back-translation,
\[
\|V(t)\|_{L^2_\omega}\lesssim
e^{-(r-b)(T-t)}\|\Phi\|_{L^1_\omega}(T-t)^{-d/4},
\]
so that decay occurs only when $r>b$.

\end{enumerate}

\medskip
\noindent\textbf{Outline of the thesis.}
In Section~\ref{sec:background} we recall the fundamental theory of the
Black--Scholes framework. Then in Section~\ref{sec:nonlinear} we
introduce the nonlinear models. In Section~\ref{sec:transform} we
transform the pricing PDE to a semilinear heat equation. Subsequently,
in Sections~\ref{sec:transform}, \ref{sec:dissipative_model}, and
\ref{sec:plus_model}, we carry out the analysis. Finally, we transport
the results back to the pricing PDE in
Section~\ref{sec:nonlinear_bs_proofs}.
