\section{Financial and Mathematical Background}
\label{sec:background}

The most important question, in the world of financial derivatives is what is their "fair price". How do you go ahead about pricing the random ups and downs that financial assets have. To answer this question we recall the classical Black-Scholes theory, upon which we will later build our semi-linear multi-asset model. 

\subsection{European options and the underlying price model}

A European option is a contract giving its holder the right, but not the obligation, to buy or sell an underlying asset at a fixed strike price \(K\) on a future date \(T\). If \(S_t\) denotes the asset price at time \(t\), then the standard payoffs at maturity are
\[
C(S,T)=(S-K)^+,
\qquad
P(S,T)=(K-S)^+,
\]
for a call and a put, respectively.

In the classical Black-Scholes model, the underlying asset is assumed to follow a geometric Brownian motion,
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:physicalSDE}
\frac{dS_t}{S_t}=\mu\,dt+\sigma\,dW_t,
\end{equation}
where \(\mu\in\mathbb R\) is the drift, \(\sigma>0\) is the volatility, and \(W_t\) is a standard Brownian motion. Under this model, \(S_t\) is lognormally distributed.

\subsection{The Black-Scholes equation}

Let \(V=V(S,t)\) denote the option price. Applying It\^o's formula to \(V(S_t,t)\), where \(S_t\) satisfies \eqref{eq:physicalSDE}, gives
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:dV}
dV
=
\Bigl(V_t+\mu S V_S+\tfrac12 \sigma^2 S^2 V_{SS}\Bigr)\,dt
+\sigma S V_S\,dW_t.
\end{equation}

To eliminate the stochastic term, one considers the self-financing portfolio
\[
\Pi=V-\Delta S.
\]
Choosing \(\Delta=V_S\) removes the stochastic component and makes the portfolio locally riskless. By the no-arbitrage principle, such a portfolio must grow at the risk-free rate \(r\), so \(d\Pi=r\Pi\,dt\). This yields the Black-Scholes equation
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:BlackScholes}
V_t+\tfrac12 \sigma^2 S^2 V_{SS}+rSV_S-rV=0.
\end{equation}

Thus the option price satisfies a linear backward parabolic partial differential equation with terminal condition
\[
V(T,S)=\Phi(S).
\]

\paragraph{Risk-neutral valuation and probabilistic interpretation.}
The above derivation is equivalent to a probabilistic pricing principle under a risk-neutral measure $\mathbb{Q}$. Under $\mathbb{Q}$, the asset dynamics become
\[
\frac{dS_t}{S_t} = r\,dt + \sigma\,dW_t^{\mathbb{Q}},
\]
and the arbitrage-free price of a European payoff $\Phi$ is given by
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:FK_BS}
V(t,S)
=
e^{-r(T-t)}\,\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}}\!\bigl[\Phi(S_T)\mid S_t=S\bigr].
\end{equation}
Here \(\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}}[\cdot\mid S_t=S]\) denotes conditional expectation under the risk-neutral probability measure \(\mathbb{Q}\), that is, expectation with respect to the law under which discounted asset prices are martingales; Wilmott \cite{Wilmott2006}.



The Black-Scholes equation \eqref{eq:BlackScholes} is the deterministic counterpart of this representation. In particular, solving the PDE with terminal condition is equivalent to evaluating the conditional expectation \eqref{eq:FK_BS}.

\subsection{Multi-asset extension}
To generalize the model for more than one variable, as in the case of the "basket option" we need to consider not only the individual volatility of one underlying asset, but also weather or not the basket constituents tend to comove. 

Let us consider a vector of asset prices
$S_t = (S_t^1,\dots,S_t^d)$ satisfying
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:multi_asset_SDE}
\frac{dS_t^i}{S_t^i}
=
\mu_i\,dt + \sum_{j=1}^d \sigma_{ij}\,dW_t^j,
\qquad i=1,\dots,d,
\end{equation}
where $\Sigma=(\sigma_{ij})$ is the volatility matrix and $W_t$ is a
$d$-dimensional Brownian motion. The matrix $\Sigma$ encodes both the
individual volatilities and the interactions between assets, while the
covariance matrix
\[
Q = \Sigma \Sigma^\top
\]
captures their joint dynamics.

Applying the vector-valued It\^o formula to $V(S_t,t)$ yields
\[
dV
=
\Bigl(
V_t + \sum_{i=1}^d \mu_i S_i V_{S_i}
+ \tfrac12 \sum_{i,j=1}^d Q_{ij} S_i S_j V_{S_i S_j}
\Bigr) dt
+ \text{stochastic terms}.
\]

Constructing a self-financing portfolio with position
$\Delta = \nabla_S V$ eliminates all stochastic components
simultaneously, provided the covariance matrix $Q$ is non-degenerate.
Imposing the no-arbitrage condition then leads to the multi-asset
Black--Scholes equation
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:BS_multi}
V_t
+
\frac12 \sum_{i,j=1}^d Q_{ij} S_i S_j V_{S_i S_j}
+
r \sum_{i=1}^d S_i V_{S_i}
-
rV
= 0.
\end{equation}

\subsection{Connection with the heat equation}

This subsection treats the single-asset case as a warm-up illustrating the transformation mechanism. The full $d$-dimensional reduction, involving covariance structure and whitening, is carried out in Section~\ref{sec:transform}.

Introduce
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:BS}
x=\log\!\left(\frac{S}{K}\right),
\qquad
\tau=\frac12 \sigma^2 (T-t),
\qquad
V(S,t)=K\,w(x,\tau).
\end{equation}
A direct computation gives
\[
w_\tau=w_{xx}+(k-1)w_x-kw,
\qquad
k=\frac{2r}{\sigma^2}.
\]
The first-order and zeroth-order terms are removed by the substitution
\[
w(x,\tau)=e^{-\frac12 (k-1)x-\frac14 (k+1)^2\tau}\,v(x,\tau),
\]
which reduces the equation to the heat equation
\[
v_\tau=v_{xx}.
\]

This shows that the Black-Scholes pricing problem is mathematically equivalent to a diffusion problem in logarithmic price variables. 

\begin{remark}[Well-posedness via the heat equation]
The transformation above converts the Black-Scholes terminal-value problem into an initial-value problem for the heat equation. Since the heat equation is well-posed in standard function spaces, existence, uniqueness, and stability follow immediately and are inherited by $V$ through the inverse transformation. This mechanism will be extended in Section~\ref{sec:transform} to treat the nonlinear multi-asset model.
\end{remark}

\subsection{Classical pricing formula}

For a European call, the previous analysis leads to the classical Black-Scholes formula.

\begin{corollary}[Black-Scholes call price formula \cite{BlackScholes1973,Merton1973}]
\label{cor:BS_formula}
For a European call with payoff \(V(T,S)=(S-K)^+\), the solution of \eqref{eq:BlackScholes} is
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:BS_call}
C(S,t)=S\,N(d_1)-Ke^{-r(T-t)}N(d_2),
\end{equation}
where
\[
d_1=\frac{\ln(S/K)+(r+\frac12\sigma^2)(T-t)}{\sigma\sqrt{T-t}},
\qquad
d_2=d_1-\sigma\sqrt{T-t},
\]
and $N$ is the standard normal cumulative distribution function.
\end{corollary}

We do not pursue the classical linear theory further, since the main goal of the thesis is to study a nonlinear multi-asset extension in which the Black-Scholes operator acquires an additional semilinear term reflecting a reduced-form asymmetric valuation adjustment.

\section{Limitations of the classical model and motivation for an extension}
\label{sec:nonlinear}


Nonlinear extensions of the Black-Scholes model have become more and more popular in the financial literature since they address some limitations and shortcomings of the standard model. For example the classical BS model fails to take into account several important factors which create friction in the real world. For example, the model assumes a universal risk free rate. This assumption fails to take into account differences in the rates between credits and deposits, as well as counterparty risk. We attempt to model these frictions by adding a nonlinear reaction term $-g(V)$ to the pricing PDE. This serves the purpose of encoding FVA and XVA adjustments. This is economically meaningful since it provides more realistic modelling of the market. We consider the nonlinearities of the form
\[
g(v)=a\,v^+ \pm b\,v^-, \qquad a,b \ge 0,
\]
where $v^+=\max(v,0)$ and $v^-=\max(-v,0)$. 

This structure reflects the asymmetry between positive and negative exposures. Lets first consider the 
\[
g(v)=a\,v^+ - b\,v^-, \qquad a,b \ge 0.
\]
This structure allows us to control the bid-ask spread between credit and deposit and provides a more realistic view of the financial reality. But also mathematically speaking these adjustments break the linearity of the pricing PDE, since they create recursive dependence since the desk must post or receive collateral in amounts dependent on the current mark-to-market value. From a mathematical perspective, the resulting equation is dissipative.

Considering the second term
\[
g(v)=a\,v^+ + b\,v^-, \qquad a,b \ge 0.
\]
Notice that when we have positive exposure the model behaves exactly as the abovementioned dissipative model. But when we have negative exposure we see that the term is discounted less strongly. TThis means that it attempts to model funding benefit effects such as an institution's own counterparty risk.

This structure can be understood as a reduced form of XVA and should be viewed as a stylized approximation rather than a full model of default. A complete XVA model would include default rates and exposure at default, which is out of the scope of the current work. Rather we look at it as an interesting mathematical case with some economic meaning.

\subsection{Market setting (classical part)}
Let $S=(S_1,\dots,S_d)\in(0,\infty)^d$ denote the vector of underlying asset prices.
In the standard risk-neutral Black-Scholes setting with constant covariance matrix $Q\in\mathbb{R}^{d\times d}$
(symmetric, positive definite), the second-order term in the pricing PDE is
\begin{equation}
\frac12\sum_{i,j=1}^d Q_{ij} S_iS_j\,\partial_{S_iS_j}V
\label{eq:bs-diffusion}
\end{equation}
The first-order term is $r\sum_i S_i \partial_{S_i}V$ and the linear discount term is $-rV$.

\subsection{Semilinear valuation adjustment}

We now extend the classical pricing equation by adding a semilinear reaction term depending only on the current mark-to-market value. This modification makes the adjustment endogenous while preserving the parabolic structure of the Black-Scholes equation. Let us start by considering the backward terminal-value problem
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
V_t
&+\frac12\sum_{i,j=1}^d Q_{ij} S_i S_j\, V_{S_iS_j}
+ r\sum_{i=1}^d S_i\, V_{S_i}
- rV
- g(V)\\
&=0,\qquad 0\le t<T.
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:nonlinearBS}
\end{equation}
with terminal condition $V(T,S)=\Phi(S)$.

\subsection{The model nonlinearities}
The core dissipative model uses the piecewise-linear specification
\begin{equation}
g_-(v) = a\,v^{+} - b\,v^{-}, \qquad a,b \ge 0,
\label{eq:g_piecewise_linear}
\end{equation}
while the non-dissipative extension uses
\begin{equation}
g_+(v) = a\,v^{+} + b\,v^{-}, \qquad a,b \ge 0.
\label{eq:g_plus_piecewise_linear}
\end{equation}
Both are globally Lipschitz and positively homogeneous of degree~$1$, so both lead to a time-independent semilinear heat equation after the transformations of Section~\ref{sec:transform}. Their analytical properties are separated later: dissipativity is introduced only for $g_-$ in Section~\ref{sec:dissipative_model}, while $g_+$ is treated in Section~\ref{sec:plus_model}.

\subsection{Assumptions on the nonlinear term \texorpdfstring{$g$}{g}}

The following assumptions are the only ones used before the dissipative and non-dissipative models are considered:
\begin{equation}
g:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R},\qquad g(0)=0,
\label{eq:g_shared_zero}
\end{equation}
and
\begin{equation}
g \text{ is globally Lipschitz.}
\label{eq:g_Lipschitz}
\end{equation}
For the piecewise-linear models above, positive homogeneity of degree~$1$ is also used to make the transformed heat equation autonomous. 

