\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusions}

Motivated by frictions in modern financial markets, we analysed valuation
adjustment models by extending the classical multi-asset Black--Scholes
framework with a semilinear adjustment term. After discounting, a logarithmic
change of variables, a moving-frame transformation, and a whitening
transformation, the Black--Scholes equation is converted into a semilinear
heat equation. This allows us to apply classical
semilinear heat equation theory to study the behaviour of the transformed
problem.

Within this framework, we established global well-posedness, instantaneous
regularization, and weighted energy identities, together with a detailed
analysis of dissipative and non-dissipative regimes.

For the dissipative model
\[
    g_-(v)=a v^+-b v^-,
\]
we obtained weighted \(L^2\)-energy estimates, \(L^2\)-contraction,
continuous dependence on the terminal payoff, weighted \(L^1\)-contraction,
and Gagliardo--Nirenberg-type decay estimates after transporting the
heat-side results back to the original Black--Scholes variables.

For the non-dissipative model
\[
    g_+(v)=a v^+ + b v^-,
\]
the transported conclusions are the shared well-posedness and
\(H^1\)-regularization results, the Gronwall \(L^2\)-bound, and the weighted
Gagliardo--Nirenberg bound with an exponential factor. The dissipative
conclusions proved for \(g_-\) rely on the sign structure
\[
    f_-(u)u\ge0
\]
and on the monotonicity assumptions used in the heat-side comparison and
contraction arguments. In contrast,
\[
    f_+(u)u=a(u^+)^2-b(u^-)^2
\]
is not sign-definite. For the non-dissipative term, we only obtain
well-posedness, instantaneous regularization, and a priori bounds of
Gronwall type, together with weighted Gagliardo--Nirenberg estimates
involving an exponential growth factor.

\paragraph{Future work}
A natural direction for future work is to extend the framework to
American-style contracts, which can be exercised at any time before or at
maturity, and to Bermudan-style contracts, which can be exercised only at
discrete dates. It would also be interesting to analyse how funding
asymmetries affect the Greeks. On the numerical side, one could connect the
present theory with its probabilistic counterpart through the nonlinear
Feynman--Kac representation and the associated theory of backward stochastic
differential equations, as developed by \cite{PardouxPeng1990,PardouxPeng1992}.


